\begin{abstract}
We present a self-contained proof of Dirac's theorem (every simple graph on $n\ge 3$ vertices with minimum degree at least $n/2$ is Hamiltonian) using the closure operation of Bondy and Chv\'atal. The writeup includes: short preliminaries (connectivity and 2-connectivity under $\delta\ge n/2$); a precise "path-closing" lemma with unified indexing; the single-edge closure equivalence and the iteration to $K_n$; sharpness examples showing the bound is best possible; brief small-$n$ sanity checks; and an appendix sketching the more direct P\'osa/Ore-style approach.
\end{abstract}

\section{Introduction and notation}
Throughout $G=(V,E)$ denotes a finite simple undirected graph, and $n=|V|$ denotes the number of vertices. We will assume $n\ge 3$ throughout (this excludes trivial small cases). For vertices $x,y\in V$ we write $xy\in E$ or $x\sim y$ to indicate adjacency. For $x\in V$ we write $\deg_G(x)$ (often simply $\deg(x)$) for its degree in $G$, and $\delta(G)=\min\{\deg_G(x):x\in V\}$ for the minimum degree. A Hamiltonian cycle is a cycle that visits every vertex once; a Hamiltonian path is a path that visits every vertex once.

The main aim is to prove the following classical result of Dirac by the closure method of Bondy--Chv\'atal.

\begin{theorem}[Dirac]
\label{thm:dirac}
Let $G$ be a simple graph on $n\ge 3$ vertices. If $\delta(G)\ge n/2$ then $G$ is Hamiltonian.
\end{theorem}

The proof given here proceeds in these steps: (i) short preliminaries about connectivity and 2-connectivity when $\delta\ge n/2$; (ii) a precise path-closing lemma for a Hamiltonian path with vertices indexed $x_0,\dots,x_{n-1}$ and carefully defined index-sets; (iii) the single-edge closure equivalence (adding an edge $uv$ with $\deg(u)+\deg(v)\ge n$ preserves Hamiltonicity), and iteration to the closure; (iv) application to Dirac's hypothesis (closure becomes $K_n$) and hence proof of Theorem~\ref{thm:dirac}; (v) sharpness with explicit bipartite examples; plus small-$n$ checks. An appendix sketches the direct P\'osa/Ore method.

\section{Preliminaries: connectivity and 2-connectivity}
We first record two easy but useful consequences of a large minimum degree.

\begin{proposition}[Connectivity and 2-connectivity]
\label{prop:conn-2conn}
Let $G$ be a simple graph on $n\ge 3$ vertices.
\begin{enumerate}[label=(\roman*)]
  \item If $\delta(G)\ge 1$ then $G$ has no isolated vertex; in particular if $\delta(G)\ge n/2$ then $G$ is connected.
  \item If $\delta(G)\ge n/2$ then $G$ is $2$-connected (i.e. has no cut-vertex).
\end{enumerate}
\end{proposition}

\begin{proof}
(i) The statement about isolated vertices is immediate. For connectedness under $\delta(G)\ge n/2$: suppose for contradiction that $G$ is disconnected. Choose a component $C$ with $r$ vertices. Since there are at least two components we have $r\le n/2$. Every vertex of $C$ has all its neighbors inside $C$, so its degree is at most $r-1\le n/2-1$, contradicting $\delta(G)\ge n/2$. Thus $G$ is connected.

(ii) Suppose $G$ has a cut-vertex $v$. Then $G-v$ has at least two components; let $C$ be one of them and let $r=|V(C)|$ be its size. Since there are at least two components in $G-v$ we have $r\le (n-1)/2$. Any vertex $w\in V(C)$ can be adjacent only to vertices in $C$ and possibly to $v$, so $\deg_G(w)\le r\le (n-1)/2<n/2$, contradicting $\delta(G)\ge n/2$. Hence no cut-vertex can exist and $G$ is $2$-connected.
\end{proof}

\begin{remark}
These simple observations are standard; they are sometimes used as preliminary reductions in other proofs of Dirac's theorem. We will not rely heavily on 2-connectivity below, but it is convenient to have this fact recorded.
\end{remark}

\section{A precise path-closing lemma}
The following lemma is the central combinatorial observation used in the closure-based proof. The statement below fixes a convenient unified indexing of the vertices of a Hamiltonian path and defines two index-sets whose intersection (guaranteed by a degree-sum condition) allows one to "splice" the path into a Hamiltonian cycle.

\begin{lemma}[Path-closing lemma]
\label{lem:path-close}
Let $G$ be a simple graph on $n\ge 3$ vertices. Suppose $P=x_0x_1\dots x_{n-1}$ is a Hamiltonian path of $G$, and write $u:=x_0$, $v:=x_{n-1}$ for its endpoints. Define the index-sets
\[
A:=\{\,i\in\{1,\dots,n-2\}: u\sim x_i\,\},\qquad
B:=\{\,i\in\{2,\dots,n-1\}: v\sim x_{i-1}\,\}.
\]
(Equivalently, $A$ indexes the interior vertices adjacent to $u$, and $B$ indexes the interior vertices whose successor along $P$ is adjacent to $v$.)

If $\deg_G(u)+\deg_G(v)\ge n$ then either $uv\in E(G)$ or $A\cap B\neq\emptyset$. Moreover, if $i\in A\cap B$ then the cycle
\[
C:=x_0\;x_i\;x_{i+1}\;\dots\;x_{n-1}\;x_{i-1}\;x_{i-2}\;\dots\;x_1\;x_0
\]
is a Hamiltonian cycle of $G$.
\end{lemma}

\begin{proof}
If $uv\in E(G)$ then $P$ together with the edge $uv$ already forms a Hamiltonian cycle and we are done. Assume therefore that $uv\notin E(G)$.

Because $P$ is a Hamiltonian path, every neighbor of $u$ except possibly $v$ lies among $x_1,\dots,x_{n-2}$, and by definition the neighbors of $u$ among those interior vertices are exactly counted by $A$. Since we have assumed $uv\notin E(G)$, it follows that
\[
\deg_G(u)=|A|.
\]
Similarly, every neighbor of $v$ except possibly $u$ lies among $x_1,\dots,x_{n-2}$; the set $B'=\{j\in\{1,\dots,n-2\}: v\sim x_j\}$ records those interior neighbors, and $B=\{j+1:j\in B'\}$ is just a shifted copy of $B'$. Because $uv\notin E(G)$ we have
\[
\deg_G(v)=|B|.
\]
Thus the hypothesis $\deg_G(u)+\deg_G(v)\ge n$ becomes
\[
|A|+|B|\ge n.\qquad(\ast)
\]
Note that $A\subseteq\{1,\dots,n-2\}$ and $B\subseteq\{2,\dots,n-1\}$; hence $A\cup B\subseteq\{1,2,\dots,n-1\}$, a set of size $n-1$. If $A\cap B=\emptyset$ then $|A|+|B|=|A\cup B|\le n-1$, contradicting $(\ast)$. Therefore $A\cap B\neq\emptyset$.

Let $i\in A\cap B$. By the definitions of $A$ and $B$ we have $u\sim x_i$ and $v\sim x_{i-1}$. Consider the closed walk
\[
x_0(=u),\;x_i,\;x_{i+1},\;\dots,\;x_{n-1}(=v),\;x_{i-1},\;x_{i-2},\;\dots,\;x_1,\;x_0.
\]
Every consecutive pair in this sequence is an edge of $G$: edges between $x_j$ and $x_{j+1}$ are edges of the original path $P$, and the edges $ux_i$ and $x_{i-1}v$ are present by choice of $i$. The walk visits every vertex exactly once before returning to $x_0$, hence it is a Hamiltonian cycle of $G$, as required.
\end{proof}

\section{Single-edge closure equivalence and the iterative closure}
We now formalize the key operation used in Bondy--Chv\'atal closure and derive the fundamental equivalence statement.

\begin{definition}[Single-edge closure]
Let $G$ be a graph on $n$ vertices and let $u,v\in V(G)$ be nonadjacent. The 
\emph{single-edge closure} of the nonedge $uv$ is the graph $G+uv$ obtained by adding the edge $uv$ to $G$.
\end{definition}

The following proposition is the elementary local step which underlies the closure method: adding an edge between two nonadjacent vertices whose degree sum is at least $n$ does not change whether the graph is Hamiltonian.

\begin{proposition}[Single-edge closure preserves Hamiltonicity]
\label{prop:single-edge-equivalence}
Let $G$ be a graph on $n$ vertices and let $u,v\in V(G)$ be nonadjacent with $\deg_G(u)+\deg_G(v)\ge n$. Then $G$ is Hamiltonian if and only if $G+uv$ is Hamiltonian.
\end{proposition}

