If $G$ is Hamiltonian then trivially $G+uv$ is Hamiltonian. Conversely, suppose $G+uv$ has a Hamiltonian cycle $C$. If $C$ does not use the edge $uv$ then $C$ is already a Hamiltonian cycle of $G$. Otherwise $C$ uses the edge $uv$; removing the edge $uv$ from $C$ yields a Hamiltonian path $P$ of $G$ with endpoints $u$ and $v$. Apply Lemma~\ref{lem:path-close} to this path $P$: since $\deg_G(u)+\deg_G(v)\ge n$ we obtain either $uv\in E(G)$ (contradiction, as we assumed $u$ and $v$ were nonadjacent in $G$) or there exists an index $i$ giving the Hamiltonian cycle
\[
x_0\;x_i\;x_{i+1}\;\dots\;x_{n-1}\;x_{i-1}\;\dots\;x_1\;x_0
\]
inside $G$. Thus $G$ itself contains a Hamiltonian cycle, completing the equivalence.
\end{proof}

