\section{Single-edge closure equivalence and the iterative closure}
We now formalize the key operation used in Bondy--Chv\'atal closure and derive the fundamental equivalence statement.

\begin{definition}[Single-edge closure]
Let $G$ be a graph on $n$ vertices and let $u,v\in V(G)$ be nonadjacent. The \emph{single-edge closure} of the nonedge $uv$ is the graph $G+uv$ obtained by adding the edge $uv$ to $G$.
\end{definition}

The following proposition is the elementary local step which underlies the closure method: adding an edge between two nonadjacent vertices whose degree sum is at least $n$ does not change whether the graph is Hamiltonian.

\begin{proposition}[Single-edge closure preserves Hamiltonicity]
\label{prop:single-edge-equivalence}
Let $G$ be a graph on $n$ vertices and let $u,v\in V(G)$ be nonadjacent with $\deg_G(u)+\deg_G(v)\ge n$. Then $G$ is Hamiltonian if and only if $G+uv$ is Hamiltonian.
\end{proposition}

\begin{proof}
If $G$ is Hamiltonian then trivially $G+uv$ is Hamiltonian. Conversely, suppose $G+uv$ has a Hamiltonian cycle $C$. If $C$ does not use the edge $uv$ then $C$ is already a Hamiltonian cycle of $G$. Otherwise $C$ uses the edge $uv$; removing the edge $uv$ from $C$ yields a Hamiltonian path $P$ of $G$ with endpoints $u$ and $v$. Apply Lemma~\ref{lem:path-close} to this path $P$: since $\deg_G(u)+\deg_G(v)\ge n$ we obtain either $uv\in E(G)$ (contradiction, as we assumed $u$ and $v$ were nonadjacent in $G$) or there exists an index $i$ giving the Hamiltonian cycle
\[
x_0\;x_i\;x_{i+1}\;\dots\;x_{n-1}\;x_{i-1}\;\dots\;x_1\;x_0
\]
inside $G$. Thus $G$ itself contains a Hamiltonian cycle, completing the equivalence.
\end{proof}

\begin{definition}[Bondy--Chv\'atal closure]
Given a graph $G$ on $n$ vertices, repeatedly choose a pair of distinct nonadjacent vertices $u,v$ with $\deg(u)+\deg(v)\ge n$ and add the edge $uv$; continue until no such pair remains. Any graph obtained in this way will be called a \emph{closure} of $G$, and we denote one (any one) by $\cl(G)$. (It is a standard fact that the final graph is independent of the order of choices; we do not need to use that fact here.)
\end{definition}

By Proposition~\ref{prop:single-edge-equivalence}, every single addition of an allowed edge preserves the property of being Hamiltonian. Iterating this observation yields the general closure equivalence.

\begin{corollary}[Bondy--Chv\'atal closure preserves Hamiltonicity]
\label{cor:closure-equiv}
For any graph $G$ on $n$ vertices and any closure $\cl(G)$ obtained by the process above, $G$ is Hamiltonian if and only if $\cl(G)$ is Hamiltonian.
\end{corollary}

\begin{proof}
Each step of the closure process adds an edge between a nonadjacent pair $u,v$ satisfying $\deg(u)+\deg(v)\ge n$, and by Proposition~\ref{prop:single-edge-equivalence} the property of being Hamiltonian is unchanged by that step. Repeating this argument for each step of the process (finitely many steps) shows that $G$ is Hamiltonian iff the final graph $\cl(G)$ is Hamiltonian.
\end{proof}

\section{Proof of Dirac's theorem via closure}
We now apply the closure machinery to deduce Dirac's theorem immediately.

\begin{proof}[Proof of Theorem~\ref{thm:dirac}]
Assume $\delta(G)\ge n/2$. Let $u,v$ be any two vertices of $G$. Then
\[
\deg_G(u)+\deg_G(v)\ge 2\delta(G)\ge n.
\]
Hence every pair of nonadjacent vertices satisfies the closure condition. Therefore when one performs the Bondy--Chv\'atal closure process on $G$, every missing edge will be eligible to be added (from the start); iteratively adding all such edges yields the complete graph $K_n$, so one possible closure is $\cl(G)=K_n$. Since $K_n$ is Hamiltonian and by Corollary~\ref{cor:closure-equiv} closure preserves Hamiltonicity, it follows that $G$ itself is Hamiltonian. This completes the proof.
\end{proof}

\section{Sharpness of the bound}
We show that the bound $\delta(G)\ge n/2$ in Dirac's theorem is best possible by providing natural non-Hamiltonian graphs whose minimum degree is just below $n/2$.

\begin{proposition}[Sharpness examples]
\label{prop:sharp}
\begin{enumerate}[label=(\alph*)]
  \item For even $n=2k\ (k\ge 2)$ the complete bipartite graph $K_{k-1,k+1}$ has $\delta= k-1= n/2-1$ and is not Hamiltonian.
  \item For odd $n=2k+1\ (k\ge 1)$ the complete bipartite graph $K_{k,k+1}$ has $\delta=k=\lfloor n/2\rfloor$ and is not Hamiltonian.
\end{enumerate}
In both cases the graphs are bipartite with parts of unequal size, so they do not contain a Hamiltonian cycle that visits all $n$ vertices.
\end{proposition}

\begin{proof}
In a bipartite graph every cycle has even length, visiting equally many vertices from each bipartition. In case (a), $K_{k-1,k+1}$ has $n=2k$ vertices but the two parts have sizes $k-1$ and $k+1$, so any cycle can include at most $2(k-1)=n-2$ vertices; hence no Hamiltonian cycle exists. The minimum degree is $\min(k-1,k+1)=k-1=n/2-1$. In case (b), $K_{k,k+1}$ has an odd total number of vertices $2k+1$, and no bipartite graph with an odd number of vertices can have a cycle that visits all vertices (since every cycle has even length). The minimum degree is $\min(k,k+1)=k=\lfloor n/2\rfloor$. Thus both families exhibit that the $n/2$ threshold cannot be lowered.
\end{proof}

\section{Small-$n$ sanity checks}
A few trivial checks for small $n$ are instructive:
\begin{itemize}
  \item $n=3$: The condition $\delta\ge n/2$ forces $\delta\ge 3/2$, hence $\delta\ge 2$. The only simple graph with three vertices and minimum degree $2$ is $K_3$, which is Hamiltonian.
  \item $n=4$: If $\delta\ge 2$ then for any two vertices $u,v$ we have $\deg(u)+\deg(v)\ge 4$, so every nonadjacent pair satisfies the closure condition and the closure is $K_4$; hence $G$ is Hamiltonian. One can also check case-by-case that no counterexamples exist.
\end{itemize}
These checks are consistent with Theorem~\ref{thm:dirac}.

\section{Concluding remarks}
The closure-based proof given above is concise and conceptually clean: one verifies a local operation that preserves Hamiltonicity, and observes that under Dirac's degree hypothesis the closure is the complete graph, which is trivially Hamiltonian. The closure method of Bondy and Chv\'atal is more general and yields the broader closure theorem (Corollary~\ref{cor:closure-equiv} together with the observation that closure does not depend on the order of additions), and it interpolates between Dirac's theorem and Ore's theorem.

