\section{Appendix: sketch of the direct P\'osa/Ore approach}
We sketch the more direct line of argument (often attributed to P\'osa and Ore) that can also be used to prove Dirac's theorem without explicitly invoking closure. Two common formulations are:
\begin{itemize}
  \item Ore's theorem: if a graph $G$ on $n\ge 3$ vertices satisfies $\deg(x)+\deg(y)\ge n$ for every pair of distinct nonadjacent vertices $x,y$, then $G$ is Hamiltonian. Dirac's theorem is an immediate corollary since $\delta\ge n/2$ implies the Ore condition.
  \item P\'osa's rotation-extension method: choose a longest path and attempt to extend it by "rotations" at one endpoint; degree conditions force a contradiction unless the path is Hamiltonian.
\end{itemize}

A brief sketch of a standard proof of Ore's theorem is as follows. Suppose $G$ satisfies the Ore condition and is not Hamiltonian. Let $P=v_0v_1\dots v_t$ be a longest path in $G$ (so $t\le n-1$ and every neighbor of $v_0$ or $v_t$ lies on $P$). Since $P$ is maximal, for every index $i$ with $1\le i\le t$ we cannot both have $v_0\sim v_i$ and $v_t\sim v_{i-1}$, because otherwise the edges $v_0v_i$ and $v_{i-1}v_t$ together with segments of $P$ would produce a cycle or a longer path contradicting maximality. Thus the sets
\[
A=\{i\in[1,t]:v_0\sim v_i\},\quad B=\{i\in[1,t]:v_t\sim v_{i-1}\}
\]
are (essentially) disjoint subsets of $\{1,\dots,t\}$, and by counting one deduces $\deg(v_0)+\deg(v_t)\le t\le n-1$, contradicting the Ore hypothesis $\deg(v_0)+\deg(v_t)\ge n$. This contradiction shows $G$ must be Hamiltonian. The full details require a careful handling of indices and the possibility of forming cycles and extending paths, but they follow the same combinatorial pattern as the path-closing lemma used above.

Both the closure method presented in the main text and the P\'osa/Ore approaches are classical and useful: the closure method is flexible (it can be used to reduce many Hamiltonicity problems to checking the complete graph), and the rotation-extension method is constructive and often used in extremal and probabilistic settings.

